# Atomic Structure and Reactivity

## Context
This week in science class, we learned about atomic structure and how elements are organized in the periodic table.

## What I Learned
This week I learned that atoms are made of electrons arranged in different energy levels, also called shells. The number and arrangement of electrons—especially in the outer shell—determine how an element reacts.

I learned that different groups in the periodic table show clear patterns of reactivity. Alkali metals (Group 1) are very reactive because they lose one electron easily. Alkaline earth metals (Group 2) are also reactive, but less than Group 1, because they lose two electrons.

Halogens (Group 17) are very reactive non-metals because they need one more electron to complete their outer shell. This makes them likely to gain electrons and form bonds.

In contrast, noble gases (Group 18) are very stable because they already have a full outer shell. As a result, they rarely react or form bonds and usually exist as individual atoms.

## Key Concept
Atoms react in order to become more stable.

Some atoms lose electrons (such as alkali metals).
Some atoms gain electrons (such as halogens).
Some atoms are already stable (such as noble gases).

This explains why chemical bonding happens: atoms are trying to achieve a full outer shell.

## Important Clarification
Noble gases do not have the most electron shells. However, they all have a full outer shell, which makes them very stable and unlikely to react.

